2.\n** [http://www.regulations.gov/#!documentDetail;D=DOT-OST-2008-0237-0028 Order 2012-10-14 (October 11, 2012)]: re-selecting Wright Air Service, Inc., to provide Essential Air Service (EAS) at Lake Minchumina, Alaska, for $102,300 annually for two nonstop round trips per week to Fairbanks \u2013 one with a 9-seat IFR Certified aircraft ([[Cessna 208]] or [[Piper Navajo]]) and one with 4-seat single-engine piston aircraft ([[Cessna 206]] or [[Beech Bonanza]]) \u2013 through October 31, 2014.\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050119193439/http://www.alaska.faa.gov/fai/images/ARPT_DIAGRAMS/MHM.gif Alaska FAA airport diagram] <small>([[GIF]])</small>\n* {{FAA-procedures|MHM}}\n{{US-airport2|MHM|PAMH}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Airports in the Yukon\u2013Koyukuk Census Area, Alaska]]\n[[Category:Essential Air Service]]\n", "name_user": "Menchi", "label": "safe", "comment": "hyphenatecompound adjectives", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minchumina_Airport"}
{"title_page": "King Salmon Airport", "text_new": "{{Infobox airport\n| name         = King Salmon Airport\n| nativename   = \n| nativename-a = \n| image        = AKN-Aerial_Map.jpg\n| image-width  = 250\n| IATA         = AKN\n| ICAO         = PAKN\n| FAA          = AKN\n| type         = Public\n| owner        = [[State of Alaska DOT&PF]] - Central Region\n| operator     = \n| city-served  = [[King Salmon, Alaska]]\n| location     = <!--if different than above-->\n| hub          = [[PenAir]]\n| elevation-f  = 73\n| website      = \n| coordinates  = {{coord|58|40|35|N|156|38|55|W|region:US-AK_scale:40000|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map            = USA Alaska\n| pushpin_mapsize        = 250\n| pushpin_map_caption    = Location of airport in Alaska\n| pushpin_label          = '''AKN'''\n| pushpin_label_position = bottom\n| r1-number    = 12/30\n| r1-length-f  = 8,901\n| r1-surface   = Asphalt\n| r2-number    = 18/36\n| r2-length-f  = 4,017\n| r2-surface   = Asphalt\n| stat-year    = 2011\n| stat1-header = Aircraft operations\n| stat1-data   = 51,300\n| stat2-header = Based aircraft\n| stat2-data   = 42\n| footnotes    = Source: [[Federal Aviation Administration]]<ref name=\"FAA\">{{FAA-airport|ID=AKN|use=PU|own=PU|site=50416.*A}}. Federal Aviation Administration. effective May 31, 2012.</ref>\n}}\n\n'''King Salmon Airport''' {{airport codes|AKN|PAKN|AKN}} is a state-owned public-use [[airport]] located just southeast of [[King Salmon, Alaska|King Salmon]], in the [[Bristol Bay Borough, Alaska|Bristol Bay Borough]] of the [[U.S. state]] of [[Alaska]].<ref name=\"FAA\" /> It was formerly the [[Naknek Air Force Base]], named for its location near the [[Naknek River]].\n\nAs per [[Federal Aviation Administration]] records, the airport had 42,310 passenger boardings (enplanements) in [[calendar year]] 2008,<ref>\n {{cite web\n | url = http://www.faa.gov/airports/planning_capacity/passenger_allcargo_stats/passenger/media/cy08_all_enplanements.pdf\n | title = Enplanements for CY 2008 | format = PDF, 1.0&nbsp;MB\n | work = [http://www.faa.gov/airports/planning_capacity/passenger_allcargo_stats/passenger/index.cfm?year=2008 CY 2008 Passenger Boarding and All-Cargo Data]\n | publisher = Federal Aviation Administration | date = December 18, 2009\n }}\n</ref> 40,637 enplanements in 2009, and 41,514 in 2010.<ref>\n {{cite web\n | url = http://www.faa.gov/airports/planning_capacity/passenger_allcargo_stats/passenger/media/cy10_all_enplanements.pdf\n | title = Enplanements for CY 2010 | format = PDF, 189&nbsp;KB\n | work = [http://www.faa.gov/airports/planning_capacity/passenger_allcargo_stats/passenger/index.cfm?year=2010 CY 2010 Passenger Boarding and All-Cargo Data]\n | publisher = Federal Aviation Administration | date = October 4, 2011\n }}\n</ref> It is included in the [[National Plan of Integrated Airport Systems]] for 2011\u20132015, which [[FAA airport categories|categorized]] it as a ''primary commercial service'' airport (more than 10,000 enplanements per year).<ref>\n {{cite web\n |url=http://www.faa.gov/airports/planning_capacity/npias/reports/media/2011/npias_2011_appA.pdf \n |title=2011\u20132015 NPIAS Report, Appendix A \n |format=[[PDF]], 2.03&nbsp;MB \n |work=[http://www.faa.gov/airports/planning_capacity/npias/reports/index.cfm?sect=2011 National Plan of Integrated Airport Systems] \n |publisher=Federal Aviation Administration \n |date=October 4, 2010 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120927084535/http://www.faa.gov/airports/planning_capacity/npias/reports/media/2011/npias_2011_appA.pdf \n |archivedate=September 27, 2012 \n}}\n</ref>\n\n==Facilities and aircraft==\nKing Salmon Airport covers an area of 5,277 [[acre]]s (2,136 [[hectare|ha]]) at an [[elevation]] of 73 feet (22&nbsp;m) above [[mean sea level]]. It has two [[asphalt]] paved [[runway]]s: 12/30 measuring 8,901 by 150 feet (2,713 \u00d7 46&nbsp;m) and 18/36 measuring 4,017 by 100 feet (1,224 \u00d7 30&nbsp;m).<ref name=FAA />\n\nFor the 12-month period ending August 12, 2011, the airport had 51,300 aircraft operations, an average of 140 per day: 66% [[general aviation]], 32% [[air taxi]], 2% [[airline|scheduled commercial]], and 1% [[military aviation|military]]. At that time there were 42 aircraft based at this airport: 79% single-[[aircraft engine|engine]], 14% multi-engine, and 7% [[helicopter]].<ref name=\"FAA\" />\n\n==Airlines and destinations==\n===Passenger===\n{{Airport destination list\n| {{nowrap|[[Alaska Airlines]]}} | '''Seasonal:''' [[Ted Stevens Anchorage International Airport|Anchorage]]\n| [[Grant Aviation]] | [[Chignik Bay Seaplane Base|Chignik Bay]], [[Chignik Lagoon Airport|Chignik Lagoon]], [[Chignik Lake Airport|Chignik Lake]], [[Clarks Point Airport|Clarks Point]], [[Dillingham Airport|Dillingham]], [[Egegik Airport|Egegik]], [[Igiugig Airport|Igiugig]], [[Levelock Airport|Levelock]], [[Perryville Airport|Perryville]], [[Pilot Point Airport|Pilot Point]], [[Port Heiden Airport|Port Heiden]], [[South Naknek Airport|South Naknek]]<br />'''Seasonal:''' [[Port Moller Airport|Port Moller]]<ref>[http://www.flygrant.com.com]{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. Grant Aviation. Retrieved 4/18/2014.</ref>\n| [[Katmai Air]]<ref name=Bo>{{cite book |last1=Bennett |first1=Bo |title=Rods & Wings |date=2000 |publisher=Publication Consultants |location=Anchorage |isbn=9781888125627 |pages=226-227}}</ref>  | [[Brooks Camp]] }}\n\n==Accidents and incidents==\nOn June 30, 1985, [[Douglas C-47|Douglas C-47B]] N168Z of Northern Peninsula Fisheries was substantially damaged at King Salmon when both engines failed on approach while the aircraft was on an executive flight from [[Homer Airport]], Alaska.<ref name=ASN300685>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19850630-0 |title=N168Z Accident description |publisher=Aviation Safety Network |accessdate=July 27, 2010}}</ref> The cause of the accident was fuel exhaustion. A fuel filler cap was discovered to be missing after the accident.<ref name=ANC85FA112>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntsb.gov/ntsb/brief.asp?ev_id=20001214X36633&key=1 |title=NTSB Identification: ANC85FA112 |publisher=National Transportation Safety Board |accessdate=July 27, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://msrmaps.com/map.aspx?t=2&s=13&lat=58.6765&lon=-156.6487&w=600&h=600&lp=---+None+--- Topographic map] from [[USGS]] ''[[The National Map]]''\n* {{FAA-diagram|01237|King Salmon (AKN)}}\n* {{FAA-procedures|AKN|King Salmon (AKN)}}\n{{US-airport2|AKN|PAKN}}\n\n[[Category:Airports in Bristol Bay Borough, Alaska]]\n\n\n{{Alaska-airport-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox airport\n| name         = King Salmon Airport\n| nativename   = \n| nativename-a = \n| image        = AKN-Aerial_Map.jpg\n| image-width  = 250\n| IATA         = AKN\n| ICAO         = PAKN\n| FAA          = AKN\n| type         = Public\n| owner        = [[State of Alaska DOT&PF]] - Central Region\n| operator     = \n| city-served  = [[King Salmon, Alaska]]\n| location     = <!--if different than above-->\n| hub          = [[PenAir]]\n| elevation-f  = 73\n| website      = \n| coordinates  = {{coord|58|40|35|N|156|38|55|W|region:US-AK_scale:40000|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map            = USA Alaska\n| pushpin_mapsize        = 250\n| pushpin_map_caption    = Location of airport in Alaska\n| pushpin_label          = '''AKN'''\n| pushpin_label_position = bottom\n| r1-number    = 12/30\n| r1-length-f  = 8,901\n| r1-surface   = Asphalt\n| r2-number    = 18/36\n| r2-length-f  = 4,017\n| r2-surface   = Asphalt\n| stat-year    = 2011\n| stat1-header = Aircraft operations\n| stat1-data   = 51,300\n| stat2-header = Based aircraft\n| stat2-data   = 42\n| footnotes    = Source: [[Federal Aviation Administration]]<ref name=\"FAA\">{{FAA-airport|ID=AKN|use=PU|own=PU|site=50416.*A}}. Federal Aviation Administration. effective May 31, 2012.</ref>\n}}\n\n'''King Salmon Airport''' {{airport codes|AKN|PAKN|AKN}} is a state owned, public use [[airport]] located just southeast of [[King Salmon, Alaska|King Salmon]], in the [[Bristol Bay Borough, Alaska|Bristol Bay Borough]] of the [[U.S. state]] of [[Alaska]].<ref name=\"FAA\" /> It was formerly the [[Naknek Air Force Base]], named for its location near the [[Naknek River]].\n\nAs per [[Federal Aviation Administration]] records, the airport had 42,310 passenger boardings (enplanements) in [[calendar year]] 2008,<ref>\n {{cite web\n | url = http://www.faa.gov/airports/planning_capacity/passenger_allcargo_stats/passenger/media/cy08_all_enplanements.pdf\n | title = Enplanements for CY 2008 | format = PDF, 1.0&nbsp;MB\n | work = [http://www.faa.gov/airports/planning_capacity/passenger_allcargo_stats/passenger/index.cfm?year=2008 CY 2008 Passenger Boarding and All-Cargo Data]\n | publisher = Federal Aviation Administration | date = December 18, 2009\n }}\n</ref> 40,637 enplanements in 2009, and 41,514 in 2010.<ref>\n {{cite web\n | url = http://www.faa.gov/airports/planning_capacity/passenger_allcargo_stats/passenger/media/cy10_all_enplanements.pdf\n | title = Enplanements for CY 2010 | format = PDF, 189&nbsp;KB\n | work = [http://www.faa.gov/airports/planning_capacity/passenger_allcargo_stats/passenger/index.cfm?year=2010 CY 2010 Passenger Boarding and All-Cargo Data]\n | publisher = Federal Aviation Administration | date = October 4, 2011\n }}\n</ref> It is included in the [[National Plan of Integrated Airport Systems]] for 2011\u20132015, which [[FAA airport categories|categorized]] it as a ''primary commercial service'' airport (more than 10,000 enplanements per year).<ref>\n {{cite web\n |url=http://www.faa.gov/airports/planning_capacity/npias/reports/media/2011/npias_2011_appA.pdf \n |title=2011\u20132015 NPIAS Report, Appendix A \n |format=[[PDF]], 2.03&nbsp;MB \n |work=[http://www.faa.gov/airports/planning_capacity/npias/reports/index.cfm?sect=2011 National Plan of Integrated Airport Systems] \n |publisher=Federal Aviation Administration \n |date=October 4, 2010 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120927084535/http://www.faa.gov/airports/planning_capacity/npias/reports/media/2011/npias_2011_appA.pdf \n |archivedate=September 27, 2012 \n}}\n</ref>\n\n==Facilities and aircraft==\nKing Salmon Airport covers an area of 5,277 [[acre]]s (2,136 [[hectare|ha]]) at an [[elevation]] of 73 feet (22&nbsp;m) above [[mean sea level]]. It has two [[asphalt]] paved [[runway]]s: 12/30 measuring 8,901 by 150 feet (2,713 \u00d7 46&nbsp;m) and 18/36 measuring 4,017 by 100 feet (1,224 \u00d7 30&nbsp;m).<ref name=FAA />\n\nFor the 12-month period ending August 12, 2011, the airport had 51,300 aircraft operations, an average of 140 per day: 66% [[general aviation]], 32% [[air taxi]], 2% [[airline|scheduled commercial]], and 1% [[military aviation|military]]. At that time there were 42 aircraft based at this airport: 79% single-[[aircraft engine|engine]], 14% multi-engine, and 7% [[helicopter]].<ref name=\"FAA\" />\n\n==Airlines and destinations==\n===Passenger===\n{{Airport destination list\n| {{nowrap|[[Alaska Airlines]]}} | '''Seasonal:''' [[Ted Stevens Anchorage International Airport|Anchorage]]\n| [[Grant Aviation]] | [[Chignik Bay Seaplane Base|Chignik Bay]], [[Chignik Lagoon Airport|Chignik Lagoon]], [[Chignik Lake Airport|Chignik Lake]], [[Clarks Point Airport|Clarks Point]], [[Dillingham Airport|Dillingham]], [[Egegik Airport|Egegik]], [[Igiugig Airport|Igiugig]], [[Levelock Airport|Levelock]], [[Perryville Airport|Perryville]], [[Pilot Point Airport|Pilot Point]], [[Port Heiden Airport|Port Heiden]], [[South Naknek Airport|South Naknek]]<br />'''Seasonal:''' [[Port Moller Airport|Port Moller]]<ref>[http://www.flygrant.com.com]{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. Grant Aviation. Retrieved 4/18/2014.</ref>\n| [[Katmai Air]]<ref name=Bo>{{cite book |last1=Bennett |first1=Bo |title=Rods & Wings |date=2000 |publisher=Publication Consultants |location=Anchorage |isbn=9781888125627 |pages=226-227}}</ref>  | [[Brooks Camp]] }}\n\n==Accidents and incidents==\nOn June 30, 1985, [[Douglas C-47|Douglas C-47B]] N168Z of Northern Peninsula Fisheries was substantially damaged at King Salmon when both engines failed on approach while the aircraft was on an executive flight from [[Homer Airport]], Alaska.<ref name=ASN300685>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19850630-0 |title=N168Z Accident description |publisher=Aviation Safety Network |accessdate=July 27, 2010}}</ref> The cause of the accident was fuel exhaustion. A fuel filler cap was discovered to be missing after the accident.<ref name=ANC85FA112>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntsb.gov/ntsb/brief.asp?ev_id=20001214X36633&key=1 |title=NTSB Identification: ANC85FA112 |publisher=National Transportation Safety Board |accessdate=July 27, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://msrmaps.com/map.aspx?t=2&s=13&lat=58.6765&lon=-156.6487&w=600&h=600&lp=---+None+--- Topographic map] from [[USGS]] ''[[The National Map]]''\n* {{FAA-diagram|01237|King Salmon (AKN)}}\n* {{FAA-procedures|AKN|King Salmon (AKN)}}\n{{US-airport2|AKN|PAKN}}\n\n[[Category:Airports in Bristol Bay Borough, Alaska]]\n\n\n{{Alaska-airport-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Menchi", "label": "safe", "comment": "hyphenatecompound adjectives", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/King_Salmon_Airport"}
{"title_page": "Copernicus Airport Wroc\u0142aw", "text_new": "{{Infobox airport\n| name         = Copernicus Airport Wroc\u0142aw\n| nativename   = <small>''Port Lotniczy Wroc\u0142aw<br> im. Miko\u0142aja Kopernika''</small>\n| nativename-a = \n| nativename-r =\n| image        = Copernicus Airport Wroc\u0142aw logo.png\n| image2       = Wroc\u0142aw, Budowa nowego terminala pasa\u017cerskiego - fotopolska.eu (279188).jpg\n| image-width  = 125\n| image2-width = 250\n| IATA         = WRO\n| ICAO         = EPWR\n| type         = Public\n| focus_city   = <div>\n* [[Enter Air]]\n* [[Ryanair Sun]]\n* [[Wizzair]]\n| owner        = [[Wroc\u0142aw]] - 49%<br />[[Lower Silesian Voivodeship|Lower Silesian]] - 31%<br />[[Przedsi\u0119biorstwo Pa\u0144stwowe \u201ePorty Lotnicze\u201d|PPPL]] - 20% \n| operator     = Wroc\u0142aw Airport Company\n| city-served  = [[Wroc\u0142aw]], [[Poland]]\n| location     = <!--If different than above-->\n| elevation-m  = 123\n| coordinates  = {{coord|51|06|34|N|016|52|49|E|region:PL|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map = Lower Silesian Voivodeship#Poland\n| pushpin_label = EPWR\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in Poland\n| website      = [http://airport.wroclaw.pl/en/ airport.wroclaw.pl]\n| metric-elev  = Y\n| metric-rwy   = Y\n| r1-number    = 11/29\n| r1-length-m  = 2,503\n| r1-surface   = [[Concrete]]/[[Asphalt]]\n| stat-year    = 2018\n| stat1-header = Number of Passengers\n| stat1-data   = 3,347,223 {{increase}}\n| stat2-header = Aircraft Movements\n| stat2-data   =17,2 {{increase}}\n| footnotes    = Source: Polish [[Aeronautical Information Publication|AIP]] at [[European Organisation for the Safety of Air Navigation|EUROCONTROL]]<ref name=\"AIP\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ead.eurocontrol.int/publicuser/protect/pu/main.jsp|title=EAD Basic - Error Page|website=www.ead.eurocontrol.int}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Copernicus Airport Wroc\u0142aw''' ({{lang-pl|Port Lotniczy Wroc\u0142aw im. [[Nicolaus Copernicus|Miko\u0142aja Kopernika]]}}) {{Airport codes|WRO|EPWR}} is an international commercial [[airport]] in [[Wroc\u0142aw]] in southwestern [[Poland]]. The airport is located {{convert|10|km|abbr=on}} southwest of the city centre, at Graniczna street 190. It has one [[runway]], one [[airport terminal|passenger terminal]], one [[cargo terminal]] and one [[general aviation]] terminal.\n\n==History==\n===Early years===\nThe airport was built in 1938 as ''Flugplatz Breslau-Sch\u00f6ngarten'' Airport for [[Germany|German]] military purposes before [[World War II]], when the city was still part of Germany.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://latamyzwroclawia.pl/historia|title=latamy z WROclawia \u00bb Maintenance Mode|website=latamyzwroclawia.pl}}</ref> It was the site of a military aviation school, the ''Luftkriegsschule Breslau-Sch\u00f6ngarten'', later renamed ''Luftkriegsschule 5''. Among the [[Luftwaffe]] units stationed here just before the war were the [[Sturzkampfgeschwader 77]], [[Kampfgeschwader 76]], and [[Kampfgeschwader 1]] \"Hindenburg\".\n\nIt was operated briefly by [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] forces following the war before being used for [[civilian]] purposes in 1945.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://airport.wroclaw.pl/en/airport/about-the-airport/history/|title=History {{!}} Port Lotniczy Wroc\u0142aw|website=airport.wroclaw.pl|access-date=2019-02-01}}</ref> Services were operated to [[Warsaw]], [[\u0141\u00f3d\u017a]], [[Pozna\u0144]] and [[Katowice]]. By 1992 destinations also included [[Krak\u00f3w]], [[Rzesz\u00f3w]], [[Gda\u0144sk]], [[Szczecin]] and [[Koszalin]].\n\n'Port Lotniczy Wroc\u0142aw S. A.' was established as a company in January 1992 and Wroc\u0142aw airport assets operated by the state-owned Polish Airports authority were transferred to the company in January 1993.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe first international flights were inaugurated in January 1993, serving [[Frankfurt]], Germany.<ref name=\":1\" /> Significant airport improvements have been completed in the late twentieth century. A new international departures terminal was opened in May 1997 followed by a new domestic terminal in November 1998.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Developments since the 2000s===\nA cargo terminal, international arrivals hall, and installation of a new [[meteorology|meteorological]] system were completed in 1999; new fire station and apron extensions in 2000.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.airport-technology.com/projects/copernicusairport/|title=Copernicus Airport, Wroc\u0142aw|website=Airport Technology|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-02-01}}</ref> A new [[air traffic control]] [[air traffic control tower|tower]] and duty-free area followed in 2001.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nOn December 6, 2005 the airport was renamed after the famous [[astronomer]] [[Nicolaus Copernicus]] (in [[Polish language|Polish]]: ''Miko\u0142aj Kopernik''),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polot.net/lotnisko_we_wroclawiu_strachowice_2011r_|title=Polot - Lotnisko we Wroc\u0142awiu Strachowice 2011r.|website=www.polot.net|language=pl|publication-date=2011-02-10|access-date=2019-02-01}}</ref> who in Wroc\u0142aw studied and received a scholarship, and in the years 1503-1538 was a [[scholaster]] of the [[Collegiate Church of the Holy Cross and St. Bartholomew, Wroc\u0142aw|Wroc\u0142aw Collegiate Holy Cross and St. Bartholomew]] on the [[Ostr\u00f3w Tumski, Wroc\u0142aw|Cathedral Island]]. The airport's new name is Copernicus Airport Wroc\u0142aw (''Port Lotniczy Wroc\u0142aw im. Miko\u0142aja Kopernika''). Terminal extensions were officially opened on the same day, increasing the airport's capacity to 750,000 passengers per year. This capacity was quickly exceeded by several hundred thousand (in the first 9 months of 2007 the airport served 972,505 passengers) so the existing terminal space was expanded by {{convert|1900|m\u00b2|0|abbr=on}} to alleviate some of the congestion, but more importantly make the terminal facilities conform to the requirements of the [[Schengen Agreement]], which was implemented at Poland's airports on 31 March 2008.\n\nOn 19 July 2006, the architectural firm JSK was chosen to design a significant airport expansion. This includes plans for a new passenger terminal (eventually, after several stages of expansion, the airport will be able to handle 7 million passengers yearly) and assorted taxiway, apron and navigation equipment improvements ([[Instrument landing system|ILS]]).<ref name=\":1\" /> Also, car parking will be expanded to 1,000 spaces. The first stage, increasing the passenger capacity to 3,5 million yearly, officially opened on February 29, 2012. However, the new terminal opened to passengers on Sunday March 11, 2012.\nin 2015 Ryanair announced that it has selected Copernicus Airport Wroc\u0142aw (''Port Lotniczy Wroc\u0142aw im. Miko\u0142aja Kopernika'') for its aircraft maintenance base. The construction of the hangar to fit 2 C-type aircraft (Boeing 737) was finished in June 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fly4free.pl/ryanair-szuka-mechanikow-lotniczych-we-wroclawiu/|title=Ryanair zak\u0142ada w\u0142asn\u0105 klas\u0119 w szkole we Wroc\u0142awiu. Absolwent mo\u017ce zarabia\u0107 nawet do 25 tys. PLN miesi\u0119cznie|website=Fly4free.pl - tanie loty i sposoby na tanie bilety lotnicze|language=pl|access-date=2019-02-01}}</ref> The airport has upgraded to ILS system from category I to category II in April 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tanie-loty.com.pl/blogi/10269-wroclaw-z-najbezpieczniejszym-lotniskiem-w-polsce-system-ils-juz-dziala.html|title=Wroc\u0142aw najbezpieczniejszym lotniskiem w Polsce. System ILS CAT II ju\u017c dzia\u0142a!|last=Ry\u015b|first=Aleksandra|website=www.tanie-loty.com.pl|language=pl|publication-date=2016-05-18|access-date=2019-02-01}}</ref>\n\nOn September 23, 2019, in [[New York City|New York]], the presidents of the USA and Poland signed a declaration on the deepening of defense cooperation, in which Wroc\u0142aw Airport was designated as the seat of the [[United States Army|US Army]] loading and unloading [[air base]].\n\n==Facilities==\nThe airport operates modern domestic, international and cargo terminals. The international terminal contains a [[duty free]] area in the international departures hall. The cargo terminal, located beside the [[Fire department|fire station]] and [[air traffic control]] tower, has a storage area of {{convert|3300|m2|abbr=on}}, a [[bonded warehouse]], freezer and radioactive materials warehouse.\n\n==Airlines and destinations==\nAll the following flights are currently suspended  because of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]:\n{{Airport-dest-list\n<!-- -->\n|[[Air France]] | [[Charles de Gaulle Airport|Paris\u2013Charles de Gaulle]]\n<!-- -->\n| [[Buzz (Ryanair)|Buzz]] | '''Seasonal charter:''' [[Corfu International Airport|Corfu]],<ref name=\"Charter.pl\">{{cite web|url=https://charterflights.r.pl|title=Charter flights|website=charterflights.r.pl|accessdate=4 September 2018}}</ref> [[Rhodes International Airport|Rhodes]],<ref name=\"Charter.pl\"/> [[Zakynthos International Airport|Zakynthos]]<ref name=\"Charter.pl\"/>\n<!-- -->\n|[[Corendon Airlines]] | '''Seasonal:''' [[Antalya Airport|Antalya]] (begins 14 June 2020)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/289062/corendon-airlines-s20-network-expansion/|title=Corendon Airlines S20 Network expansion|website=Routesonline|accessdate=Mar 7, 2020}}</ref>\n<!-- -->\n|[[Enter Air]]| '''Charter:''' [[Antalya Airport|Antalya]],<ref name=\"TUI.pl\"/> [[Hurghada International Airport|Hurghada]],<ref name=\"TUI.pl\"/> [[Marsa Alam International Airport|Marsa Alam]]<ref name=\"TUI.pl\"/> [[Tenerife South Airport|Tenerife\u2013South]]<ref name=\"TUI.pl\"/> <br>'''Seasonal charter:''' [[Milas\u2013Bodrum Airport|Bodrum]],<ref name=\"TUI.pl\"/> [[Burgas Airport|Burgas]],<ref name=\"TUI.pl\">{{cite web|title=Charter flights |url=https://www.tui.pl/tanie-bilety-lotnicze?pm_source=MENU&pm_name=Bilety_czarterowe|website=TUI.pl}}</ref> [