r|Yakutat Army Airfield}}\n| image        = Yakutat Airport, Alaska, US.jpg\n| image-width  = 250\n| IATA         = YAK\n| ICAO         = PAYA\n| FAA          = YAK\n| WMO = 70361\n| type         = Public\n| owner        = [[State of Alaska DOT&PF]] - Southeast Region\n| operator     = \n| city-served  = [[Yakutat, Alaska]]\n| location     = <!--if different than above-->\n| elevation-f  = 33\n| elevation-m  = 10\n| website      = \n| coordinates  = {{coord|59|30|12|N|139|39|37|W|region:US-AK|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map            = USA Alaska\n| pushpin_mapsize        = 250\n| pushpin_map_caption    = Location of airport in Alaska\n| pushpin_label          = '''YAK'''\n| pushpin_label_position = left\n| r1-number    = 2/20\n| r1-length-f  = 6,475\n| r1-length-m  = 1,974\n| r1-surface   = Concrete\n| r2-number    = 11/29\n| r2-length-f  = 7,745\n| r2-length-m  = 2,361\n| r2-surface   = Asphalt\n| stat-year    = 2010\n| stat1-header = Aircraft operations\n| stat1-data   = 19,026\n| stat2-header = Based aircraft\n| stat2-data   = 8\n| footnotes    = Source: [[Federal Aviation Administration]]<ref name=\"FAA\">{{FAA-airport|ID=YAK|use=PU|own=PU|site=50920.*A}}. Federal Aviation Administration. effective April 5, 2012.</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Yakutat Airport''' {{airport codes|YAK|PAYA|YAK}} is a state owned, public use [[airport]] located three&nbsp;[[nautical mile]]s (6&nbsp;[[kilometre|km]]) southeast of the [[central business district]] of [[Yakutat, Alaska|Yakutat]], a city and [[Borough (United States)|borough]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Alaska]] which has no road access to the outside world.<ref name=\"FAA\" /> Airline service is subsidized by the [[Essential Air Service]] program.\n\nAs per [[Federal Aviation Administration]] records, the airport had 11,028 passenger boardings (enplanements) in [[calendar year]] 2008,<ref>\n {{cite web\n | url = http://www.faa.gov/airports/planning_capacity/passenger_allcargo_stats/passenger/media/cy08_all_enplanements.pdf\n | title = Enplanements for CY 2008 | format = PDF, 1.0 MB\n | work =  CY 2008 Passenger Boarding and All-Cargo Data\n | publisher = Federal Aviation Administration | date = December 18, 2009\n }}\n</ref> 12,158 enplanements in 2009, and 10,035 in 2010.<ref>\n {{cite web\n | url = http://www.faa.gov/airports/planning_capacity/passenger_allcargo_stats/passenger/media/cy10_all_enplanements.pdf\n | title = Enplanements for CY 2010 | format = PDF, 189 KB\n | work = 2010 Passenger Boarding and All-Cargo Data\n | publisher = Federal Aviation Administration | date = October 4, 2011\n }}\n</ref> It is included in the [[National Plan of Integrated Airport Systems]] for 2015-2019, which [[FAA airport categories|categorized]] it as a ''primary commercial service (nonhub)'' airport (more than 10,000 enplanements per year) based on 10,100 enplanements in CY 2012.<ref>\n{{cite web\n  | url = http://www.faa.gov/airports/planning_capacity/npias/reports/media/npias-2015-2019-report-appendix-a.pdf\n  | title = Appendix A: List of NPIAS Airports with 5-Year Forecast Activity and Development Estimate\n  | website = National Plan of Integrated Airport Systems (NPIAS) Report\n  | publisher = Federal Aviation Administration\n  | format = PDF\n  | access-date = May 23, 2016\n  }}\n</ref>\n\n==History==\nYakutat Airport origins date from 1940 when [[Yakutat Army Airfield]] was constructed as part of the United States Army's long-range defense program for Alaska.\n\n==Facilities and aircraft==\nYakutat Airport has two [[runway]]s: 2/20 is 6,475 by 150 feet (1,974 x 46 m) with a [[concrete]] surface; 11/29 is 7,745 by 150 feet (2,361 x 46 m) with an [[asphalt]] surface.<ref name=\"FAA\" />\n\nFor the 12-month period ending May 3, 2010, the airport had 19,026 aircraft operations, an average of 52 per day: 68% [[general aviation]], 26% [[air taxi]], 4% [[airline|scheduled commercial]], and 2% [[military aviation|military]]. At that time there were 8 aircraft based at this airport, all single-[[aircraft engine|engine]].<ref name=\"FAA\" />\n\n==Airline and destinations==\n===Passenger===\n{{Airport destination list\n| [[Alaska Airlines]] | [[Ted Stevens Anchorage International Airport|Anchorage]], [[Merle K. (Mudhole) Smith Airport|Cordova]], [[Juneau International Airport|Juneau]], [[Seattle/Tacoma International Airport|Seattle/Tacoma]]\n}}\n\nAlaska Air Cargo operates the [[Boeing 737-700]] into the airport.\n\n===Top destinations===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|+ '''Busiest domestic routes out of YAK<br />(Dec 2015 - Nov 2016)''' <ref>http://www.transtats.bts.gov/airports.asp?pn=1&Airport=YAK&Airport_Name=Yakutat,%20AK:%20Yakutat%20Airport&carrier=FACTS</ref>\n! Rank\n! City\n! Passengers\n! Carriers\n|-\n| 1\n| [[Ted Stevens Anchorage International Airport|Anchorage, AK]]\n| 3,810\n| Alaska\n|-\n| 2\n| [[Juneau International Airport|Juneau, AK]]\n| 3,540\n| Alaska\n|-\n| 3\n| [[Seattle\u2013Tacoma International Airport|Seattle/Tacoma, WA]]\n| 3,330\n| Alaska\n|-\n| 4\n| [[Merle K. (Mudhole) Smith Airport|Cordova, AK]]\n| 110\n| Alaska\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Other sources==\n{{refbegin}}\n* Essential Air Service documents ([http://www.regulations.gov/#!docketDetail;D=DOT-OST-1998-4899 Docket OST-1998-4899]) from the [[U.S. Department of Transportation]]:\n** [http://www.regulations.gov/#!documentDetail;D=DOT-OST-1998-4899-0056 Order 2004-5-5 (May 4, 2004)]: tentatively reselects Alaska Airlines, Inc., to provide subsidized essential air service at Cordova, Gustavus, Petersburg, Wrangell, and Yakutat (southeast) Alaska, for the period from October 1, 2003, through April 30, 2006, at an annual rate of $5,723,008.\n** [http://www.regulations.gov/#!documentDetail;D=DOT-OST-1998-4899-0062 Order 2006-3-20 (March 22, 2006)]: re-selecting Alaska Airlines, Inc., to provide subsidized essential air service at Cordova, Gustavus, Petersburg, Wrangell, and Yakutat (southeast) Alaska, for the period from May 1, 2006, through Apr