{"title_page": "Pattimura International Airport", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox airport\n| name         = Pattimura Airport \n| nativename   = <small>{{lang|id|Bandar Udara Pattimura }}</small>\n| image        = Pattimuraairportlogo.png\n| image2       = PattimuraAirportTerminal.jpg\n| image-width  = 250\n| image2-width = 250\n| IATA         = AMQ\n| ICAO         = WAPP\n| WMO          = 97724\n| image_map              = \n| image_map_caption      = \n| pushpin_map            = Indonesia Seram#Indonesia Maluku#Indonesia\n| pushpin_label          = '''AMQ'''\n| pushpin_map_caption    = Location of airport in Maluku / Indonesia\n| pushpin_label_position = top \n| type         = Public\n| owner        = [[Government of Indonesia]]\n| operator     = [[Angkasa Pura|PT Angkasa Pura I]]\n| city-served  = [[Ambon, Maluku|Ambon]]\n| location     = [[Ambon, Maluku|Ambon]], [[Maluku (province)|Maluku]], [[Indonesia]]\n| timezone     = [[Eastern Indonesian Time|WIT]]\n| utc          = [[UTC+09:00]]\n| elevation-f  = 33\n| elevation-m  = 10\n| coordinates  = {{coord|03|42|36.95|S|128|05|20.89|E|type:airport}}\n| website      = http://www.pattimura-airport.co.id\n| metric-rwy   = yes\n| r1-number    = 04/22\n| r1-length-m  = 2,500\n| r1-surface   = [[Asphalt]]\n| stat-year    = 2017\n| stat1-header = Passengers\n| stat1-data   = 1,364,210\n| stat2-header = \n| stat2-data   = \n| stat3-header = \n| stat3-data   = \n| footnotes    = Sources: [[List of the busiest airports in Indonesia]]\n}}\n\n'''Pattimura Airport''' ({{lang-id|Bandar Udara Pattimura}}) {{airport codes|AMQ|WAPP}} is an airport in [[Ambon, Maluku|Ambon]], [[Maluku (province)|Maluku]]. The airport is located 38 kilometers west of the city of Ambon. The airport was named after [[Pattimura]], an [[National Hero of Indonesia|Indonesian national hero]] who fought against the Dutch colonialists in the nineteenth century. Pattimura Airport is an airport located in Ambon City, Maluku Province, Indonesia. The airport also caters for domestic and overseas trips. The airport is 35 kilometers outside Ambon City with travel time approximately 30\u201345 minutes. At this airport there are immigration facilities, quarantine, customs, cargo building, restaurant, public phone, and post office. Pattimura Airport Ambon is a very strategic area in the Maluku Islands which is divided into two provinces namely, North Maluku and Maluku.\nPattimura Ambon Airport is located in Ambon Island, located in Maluku Province.\n\n==History==\nThe airport was established by the Dutch in 1939 as '''Laha Airfield'''. In early February 1942, the airport was captured by the Japanese in the [[Battle of Ambon]] and used as a base for the Japanese to do battle against the allied forces in the Pacific.\nAfter the independence of Indonesia was proclaimed, Pattimura was used as an air base. This lasted until August 1, 1962, when the government formed a working unit in charge of organizing the civil aviation maintenance and operation of airports for the benefit of civil air transport. Pattimura Airport continued to be operated as an Air Force Air Base. Based on the Joint Decree of the Minister of Defense / Armed Forces Commander, Minister of Transportation and Minister of Finance, in 1975, Pattimura airport was designated as a civilian airfield and came under the full control of the Department of Transportation. On October 11, 1995, the management of the Pattimura Airport was transferred to PT. Angkasa Pura I (Persero), a state-owned enterprises that manages several airports in central and eastern Indonesia.\n\n== Facilities ==\nThis airport is located 36 kilometers from the city of Ambon.<ref>Ambon City Government Website | http://www.ambon.go.id/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=19&Itemid=26</ref> It has an immigration office, a quarantine facility, a tax office, a cargo storage building, several small restaurants, public pay phones, and a post office. Free wi-fi internet is available throughout the airport.\n\nThe international terminal is 1,200 m<sup>2</sup> (gates C & D) and has an annual capacity of 70,000 passengers.  The domestic terminal is 7,393 m<sup>2</sup> (gates A & B) and has an annual capacity of 406,000 passengers.\n\nCurrently there are no regularly scheduled international flights to or from Ambon, so the international terminal is used for domestic flights which are operated with larger airplanes and can make use of the two jet bridges for easier loading and unloading of the airplanes \u2013 especially during rain.\n\nThe cargo terminal size is 1,192 m<sup>2</sup>. The outside parking area is 8,574 m<sup>2</sup>.<ref>Angkasapura 1 website | {{cite web |url=http://www.angkasapura1.co.id/isi.php?option=ambon |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-09-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101007085507/http://www.angkasapura1.co.id/isi.php?option=ambon |archivedate=7 October 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Airlines and destinations==\n===Passenger===\n{{airport-dest-list\n|[[Airfast Indonesia]] | '''Charter:''' [[Sam Ratulangi International Airport|Manado]] \n|[[Aviastar (Indonesia)|Aviastar]] | [[Bandanaira Airport|Banda]], [[Namlea Airport|Namlea]], [[Namrole Airport|Namrole]]\n|[[Batik Air]] | [[Halim Perdanakusuma International Airport|Jakarta\u2013Halim Perdanakusuma]], [[Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport|Jakarta\u2013Soekarno-Hatta]], [[Sultan Hasanuddin International Airport|Makassar]]\n|[[Citilink]] | [[Sultan Hasanuddin International Airport|Makassar]]\n|[[Dimonim Air]] | [[Jos Orno Imsula Airport|Moa]]\n|[[Garuda Indonesia]] | [[Ngurah Rai International Airport|Denpasar/Bali]], [[Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport|Jakarta\u2013Soekarno-Hatta]],  [[Sultan Hasanuddin International Airport|Makassar]], [[Sultan Babullah Airport|Ternate]]\n|[[Lion Air]] | [[Sultan Hasanuddin International Airport|Makassar]], [[Juanda International Airport|Surabaya]]  \n|[[Sriwijaya Air]]| [[Sultan Babullah Airport|Ternate]]\n|[[Susi Air]] | [[Bandanaira Airport|Banda]], [[Namlea Airport|Namlea]] \n|[[Trigana Air Service]] | [[Dobo Airport|Dobo]], [[Karel Sadsuitubun Airport|Langgur]], [[Jos Orno Imsula Airport|Moa]], [[Namrole Airport|Namrole]], [[Saumlaki Airport|Saumlaki]]\n|[[Wings Air]] | [[Dobo Airport|Dobo]], [[Karel Sadsuitubun Airport|Langgur]], [[Sam Ratulangi International Airport|Manado]],  [[Nabire Airport|Nabire]], [[Namlea Airport|Namlea]], [[Sorong Airport|Sorong]], [[Saumlaki Airport|Saumlaki]] \n}}\n\n==Proposed development==\nPattimura Airport has a capacity of 800 thousand people, while in fact, the airport has served 1.3 million people per year. Therefore, when hearing the news, Minister of State-Owned Enterprises (SOE), Rini M. Soemarmo immediately followed up the report by telephoning the main director of Angkasa Pura (AP) I. According to AP I president, airport development has been planned. This is evidenced by the absence of development design, namely the addition of one terminal, including the addition of garbarata. Despite the news, the minister is still worried that by the end of 2017 the total number of passengers will be 1.5 million.\n\n==Former foreign routes==\nSince 1998, there have been no international routes operating out of the Pattimura International Airport.  Previously there was a flight from Ambon to Darwin, Australia.  There have been occasional flights to Darwin at the time of the various boating events, but no regularly scheduled international flights since 1998.  Recently there has been talk of resuming international flights out of Ambon, but nothing specific has been announced yet.<ref>{{cite news|work=malukuprov.go.id|title=Spacecon Rencana Bangun Victoria Park Park dalam 3 Tahun|date=8 June 2012|url=http://www.malukuprov.go.id/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=177:spacecon-rencana-bangun-victoria-park-park-dalam-3-tahun&catid=50:headline-news&Itemid=34|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023145426/http://www.malukuprov.go.id/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=177%3Aspacecon-rencana-bangun-victoria-park-park-dalam-3-tahun&catid=50%3Aheadline-news&Itemid=34|archivedate=23 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Land transportation==\n=== DAMRI Bus ===\n[[Perum DAMRI]] has buses operated to connect the airport to the surrounding area. During this time, this bus journey only has one route. The route is Pattimura International Airport-Merdeka Square.\nBus routes from the airport to Lapangan Merdeka are as follows.\nPattimura-Hative Besar Besar-Wayame-Poka -Humah Tiga-Waiheru- Nania-Passo-Lateri-Halong-Galala-Batu Batu-Kantor DPRD-Hotel Manise-Hotel Amboina-Tugu Trikora-Mangga Dua-Insurance Office Jasindo Ambon-Hotel Abdulalie -The AY Path Patty-Lapangan Merdeka.\nBus routes from Merdeka Square to the airport are as follows.\nMerdeka-Supermarket Ground-Citra-Batu Merah-Galala-Halong-Lateri-Passo-Nania-Waiheru-Poka-Big Three-Wayame-Hative House-Pattimura Airport\n\n=== Taxi ===\n[[Taksi]]\nTaxis also operate to connect this airport. Taxis serving this airport has two types of cars, namely sedans and minibuses. In the past, passengers still had to pay a ferry to cross Ambon Bay. However, there is now a Red and White Bridge that shorten the time.\n\n==Incidents==\n* On 24 July 1992, [[Mandala Airlines Flight 660]] crashed when on approach to Pattimura Airport. All 70 passengers and crew on board were killed.\n* On 7 June 1997, a [[Merpati Nusantara Airlines]] flight collided with a tree on approach but was able to land safely.<ref>{{cite news|work=Aviation Safety Network|title=Accident description|date=7 June 1997|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19970607-2}}</ref>\n* On 2 January 2007, [[Lion Air]] Flight JT 797 skidded on the runway stopping just 4 meters before the end of the runway.  Neither the plane nor any of the passengers were injured, but a runway light was damaged.  The accident occurred at 8:14am during heavy rains.<ref>{{cite news|work=ANTARA|title=Lion Air Plane Skids|date=2 January 2007|url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/article-1G1-156594211/lion-air-plane-skids.html}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.ap1.co.id/contents/file/142-Annual_Report_PT_Angkasa_Pura_I_(Persero)_2016_LR.pdf PT Angkasa Pura I 2016 Annual Report ]\n\n{{Airports in Indonesia}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[category:ambon]]\n[[Category:Airports in Maluku]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox airport\n| name         = Pattimura Airport \n| nativename   = <small>{{lang|id|Bandar Udara Pattimura }}</small>\n| image        = Pattimuraairportlogo.png\n| image2       = PattimuraAirportTerminal.jpg\n| image-width  = 250\n| image2-width = 250\n| IATA         = AMQ\n| ICAO         = WAPP\n| WMO          = 97724\n| image_map              = \n| image_map_caption      = \n| pushpin_map            = Indonesia Seram#Indonesia Maluku#Indonesia\n| pushpin_label          = '''AMQ'''\n| pushpin_map_caption    = Location of airport in Maluku / Indonesia\n| pushpin_label_position = top \n| type         = Public\n| owner        = [[Government of Indonesia]]\n| operator     = [[Angkasa Pura|PT Angkasa Pura I]]\n| city-served  = [[Ambon, Maluku|Ambon]]\n| location     = [[Ambon, Maluku|Ambon]], [[Maluku (province)|Maluku]], [[Indonesia]]\n| timezone     = [[Eastern Indonesian Time|WIT]]\n| utc          = [[UTC+09:00]]\n| elevation-f  = 33\n| elevation-m  = 10\n| coordinates  = {{coord|03|42|36.95|S|128|05|20.89|E|type:airport}}\n| website      = http://www.pattimura-airport.co.id\n| metric-rwy   = yes\n| r1-number    = 04/22\n| r1-length-m  = 2,500\n| r1-surface   = [[Asphalt]]\n| stat-year    = 2017\n| stat1-header = Passengers\n| stat1-data   = 1,364,210\n| stat2-header = \n| stat2-data   = \n| stat3-header = \n| stat3-data   = \n| footnotes    = Sources: [[List of the busiest airports in Indonesia]]\n}}\n\n'''Pattimura Airport''' ({{lang-id|Bandar Udara Pattimura}}) {{airport codes|AMQ|WAPP}} is an airport in [[Ambon, Maluku|Ambon]], [[Maluku (province)|Maluku]]. The airport is located 38 kilometers west of the city of Ambon. The airport was named after [[Pattimura]], an [[National Hero of Indonesia|Indonesian national hero]] who fought against the Dutch colonialists in the nineteenth century. Pattimura Airport is an airport located in Ambon City, Maluku Province, Indonesia. The airport also caters for domestic and overseas trips. The airport is 35 kilometers outside Ambon City with travel time approximately 30\u201345 minutes. At this airport there are immigration facilities, quarantine, customs, cargo building, restaurant, public phone, and post office. Pattimura Airport Ambon is a very strategic area in the Maluku Islands which is divided into two provinces namely, North Maluku and Maluku.\nPattimura Ambon Airport is located in Ambon Island, located in Maluku Province.\n\n==History==\nThe airport was established by the Dutch in 1939 as '''Laha Airfield'''. In early February 1942, the airport was captured by the Japanese in the [[Battle of Ambon]] and used as a base for the Japanese to do battle against the allied forces in the Pacific.\nAfter the independence of Indonesia was proclaimed, Pattimura was used as an air base. This lasted until August 1, 1962, when the government formed a working unit in charge of organizing the civil aviation maintenance and operation of airports for the benefit of civil air transport. Pattimura Airport continued to be operated as an Air Force Air Base. Based on the Joint Decree of the Minister of Defense / Armed Forces Commander, Minister of Transportation and Minister of Finance, in 1975, Pattimura airport was designated as a civilian airfield and came under the full control of the Department of Transportation. On October 11, 1995, the management of the Pattimura Airport was transferred to PT. Angkasa Pura I (Persero), a state owned enterprises that manages several airports in central and eastern Indonesia.\n\n== Facilities ==\nThis airport is located 36 kilometers from the city of Ambon.<ref>Ambon City Government Website | http://www.ambon.go.id/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=19&Itemid=26</ref> It has an immigration office, a quarantine facility, a tax office, a cargo storage building, several small restaurants, public pay phones, and a post office. Free wi-fi internet is available throughout the airport.\n\nThe international terminal is 1,200 m<sup>2</sup> (gates C & D) and has an annual capacity of 70,000 passengers.  The domestic terminal is 7,393 m<sup>2</sup> (gates A & B) and has an annual capacity of 406,000 passengers.\n\nCurrently there are no regularly scheduled international flights to or from Ambon, so the international terminal is used for domestic flights which are operated with larger airplanes and can make use of the two jet bridges for easier loading and unloading of the airplanes \u2013 especially during rain.\n\nThe cargo terminal size is 1,192 m<sup>2</sup>. The outside parking area is 8,574 m<sup>2</sup>.<ref>Angkasapura 1 website | {{cite web |url=http://www.angkasapura1.co.id/isi.php?option=ambon |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-09-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101007085507/http://www.angkasapura1.co.id/isi.php?option=ambon |archivedate=7 October 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Airlines and destinations==\n===Passenger===\n{{airport-dest-list\n|[[Airfast Indonesia]] | '''Charter:''' [[Sam Ratulangi International Airport|Manado]] \n|[[Aviastar (Indonesia)|Aviastar]] | [[Bandanaira Airport|Banda]], [[Namlea Airport|Namlea]], [[Namrole Airport|Namrole]]\n|[[Batik Air]] | [[Halim Perdanakusuma International Airport|Jakarta\u2013Halim Perdanakusuma]], [[Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport|Jakarta\u2013Soekarno-Hatta]], [[Sultan Hasanuddin International Airport|Makassar]]\n|[[Citilink]] | [[Sultan Hasanuddin International Airport|Makassar]]\n|[[Dimonim Air]] | [[Jos Orno Imsula Airport|Moa]]\n|[[Garuda Indonesia]] | [[Ngurah Rai International Airport|Denpasar/Bali]], [[Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport|Jakarta\u2013Soekarno-Hatta]],  [[Sultan Hasanuddin International Airport|Makassar]], [[Sultan Babullah Airport|Ternate]]\n|[[Lion Air]] | [[Sultan Hasanuddin International Airport|Makassar]], [[Juanda International Airport|Surabaya]]  \n|[[Sriwijaya Air]]| [[Sultan Babullah Airport|Ternate]]\n|[[Susi Air]] | [[Bandanaira Airport|Banda]], [[Namlea Airport|Namlea]] \n|[[Trigana Air Service]] | [[Dobo Airport|Dobo]], [[Karel Sadsuitubun Airport|Langgur]], [[Jos Orno Imsula Airport|Moa]], [[Namrole Airport|Namrole]], [[Saumlaki Airport|Saumlaki]]\n|[[Wings Air]] | [[Dobo Airport|Dobo]], [[Karel Sadsuitubun Airport|Langgur]], [[Sam Ratulangi International Airport|Manado]],  [[Nabire Airport|Nabire]], [[Namlea Airport|Namlea]], [[Sorong Airport|Sorong]], [[Saumlaki Airport|Saumlaki]] \n}}\n\n==Proposed development==\nPattimura Airport has a capacity of 800 thousand people, while in fact, the airport has served 1.3 million people per year. Therefore, when hearing the news, Minister of State-Owned Enterprises (SOE), Rini M. Soemarmo immediately followed up the report by telephoning the main director of Angkasa Pura (AP) I. According to AP I president, airport development has been planned. This is evidenced by the absence of development design, namely the addition of one terminal, including the addition of garbarata. Despite the news, the minister is still worried that by the end of 2017 the total number of passengers will be 1.5 million.\n\n==Former foreign routes==\nSince 1998, there have been no international routes operating out of the Pattimura International Airport.  Previously there was a flight from Ambon to Darwin, Australia.  There have been occasional flights to Darwin at the time of the various boating events, but no regularly scheduled international flights since 1998.  Recently there has been talk of resuming international flights out of Ambon, but nothing specific has been announced yet.<ref>{{cite news|work=malukuprov.go.id|title=Spacecon Rencana Bangun Victoria Park Park dalam 3 Tahun|date=8 June 2012|url=http://www.malukuprov.go.id/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=177:spacecon-rencana-bangun-victoria-park-park-dalam-3-tahun&catid=50:headline-news&Itemid=34|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023145426/http://www.malukuprov.go.id/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=177%3Aspacecon-rencana-bangun-victoria-park-park-dalam-3-tahun&catid=50%3Aheadline-news&Itemid=34|archivedate=23 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Land transportation==\n=== DAMRI Bus ===\n[[Perum DAMRI]] has buses operated to connect the airport to the surrounding area. During this time, this bus journey only has one route. The route is Pattimura International Airport-Merdeka Square.\nBus routes from the airport to Lapangan Merdeka are as follows.\nPattimura-Hative Besar Besar-Wayame-Poka -Humah Tiga-Waiheru- Nania-Passo-Lateri-Halong-Galala-Batu Batu-Kantor DPRD-Hotel Manise-Hotel Amboina-Tugu Trikora-Mangga Dua-Insurance Office Jasindo Ambon-Hotel Abdulalie -The AY Path Patty-Lapangan Merdeka.\nBus routes from Merdeka Square to the airport are as follows.\nMerdeka-Supermarket Ground-Citra-Batu Merah-Galala-Halong-Lateri-Passo-Nania-Waiheru-Poka-Big Three-Wayame-Hative House-Pattimura Airport\n\n=== Taxi ===\n[[Taksi]]\nTaxis also operate to connect this airport. Taxis serving this airport has two types of cars, namely sedans and minibuses. In the past, passengers still had to pay a ferry to cross Ambon Bay. However, there is now a Red and White Bridge that shorten the time.\n\n==Incidents==\n* On 24 July 1992, [[Mandala Airlines Flight 660]] crashed when on approach to Pattimura Airport. All 70 passengers and crew on board were killed.\n* On 7 June 1997, a [[Merpati Nusantara Airlines]] flight collided with a tree on approach but was able to land safely.<ref>{{cite news|work=Aviation Safety Network|title=Accident description|date=7 June 1997|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19970607-2}}</ref>\n* On 2 January 2007, [[Lion Air]] Flight JT 797 skidded on the runway stopping just 4 meters before the end of the runway.  Neither the plane nor any of the passengers were injured, but a runway light was damaged.  The accident occurred at 8:14am during heavy rains.<ref>{{cite news|work=ANTARA|title=Lion Air Plane Skids|date=2 January 2007|url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/article-1G1-156594211/lion-air-plane-skids.html}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.ap1.co.id/contents/file/142-Annual_Report_PT_Angkasa_Pura_I_(Persero)_2016_LR.pdf PT Angkasa Pura I 2016 Annual Report ]\n\n{{Airports in Indonesia}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[category:ambon]]\n[[Category:Airports in Maluku]]\n", "name_user": "Menchi", "label": "safe", "comment": "hyphenatecompound adjectives", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pattimura_International_Airport"}
{"title_page": "Nome Airport", "text_new": "{{Infobox airport\n| name         = Nome Airport\n| nativename   = \n| image        = OME-d.jpg\n| image-width  = 250\n| IATA         = OME\n| ICAO         = PAOM\n| FAA          = OME\n| WMO = 70200\n| type         = Public\n| owner        = [[Alaska DOT&PF]] - Northern Region\n| operator     =\n| city-served  = [[Nome, Alaska]]\n| location     = <!--only if different-->\n| elevation-f  = 38\n| coordinates  = {{coord|64|30|44|N|165|26|43|W|region:US-AK_type:airport|display=inline,title}}\n| website      = \n| hub          = [[Bering Air]]\n| pushpin_map            = USA Alaska\n| pushpin_mapsize        = 250\n| pushpin_map_caption    = Location of airport in Alaska\n| pushpin_label          = '''OME'''\n| pushpin_label_position = bottom\n| r1-number    = 10/28\n| r1-length-f  = 6,000\n| r1-surface   = Asphalt\n| r2-number    = 3/21\n| r2-length-f  = 6,175\n| r2-surface   = Asphalt\n| stat-year    = 2010\n| stat1-header = Aircraft operations\n| stat1-data   = 28,000\n| stat2-header = Based aircraft\n| stat2-data   = 71\n| footnotes    = Source: [[Federal Aviation Administration]]<ref name=\"FAA\">{{FAA-airport|ID=OME|use=PU|own=PU|site=50540.*A}}. Federal Aviation Administration. effective May 31, 2012.</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Nome Airport''' {{airport codes|OME|PAOM|OME}} is a state-owned public-use [[airport]] located two&nbsp;[[nautical mile]]s (4&nbsp;[[kilometre|km]]) west of the [[central business district]] of [[Nome, Alaska|Nome]], a city in the [[Nome Census Area, Alaska|Nome Census Area]] of the [[U.S. state]] of [[Alaska]].<ref name=\"FAA\" />\n\nAs per [[Federal Aviation Administration]] records, the airport had 61,651 passenger boardings (enplanements) in [[calendar year]] 2017, and 64,122 enplanements in 2018<ref>\n {{cite web\n | url = https://www.faa.gov/airports/planning_capacity/passenger_allcargo_stats/passenger/media/cy18-all-enplanements.pdf\n | title = Calendar Year 2018 Final Revenue Enplanements at All Airports | format = PDF, 1.0 MB\n | publisher = Federal Aviation Administration | date = December 20, 2019\n }}\n</ref> It is included in the [[National Plan of Integrated Airport Systems]] for 2011\u20132015, which [[FAA airport categories|categorized]] it as a ''primary commercial service'' airport (more than 10,000 enplanements per year).<ref>\n {{cite web\n | url = http://www.faa.gov/airports/planning_capacity/npias/reports/media/2011/npias_2011_appA.pdf\n | title = 2011\u20132015 NPIAS Report, Appendix A | format = [[PDF]], 2.03 MB\n | work = [http://www.faa.gov/airports/planning_capacity/npias/reports/index.cfm?sect=2011 National Plan of Integrated Airport Systems]\n | publisher = Federal Aviation Administration | date = October 4, 2010\n }}\n</ref>\n\nThe State of Alaska also operates [[Nome City Field]] {{airport codes|||94Z}}, a public [[general aviation]] airfield located one nautical mile (1.85 [[kilometre|km]]) north of the city.<ref>{{FAA-airport|ID=94Z|use=PU|own=PU|site=50538.*A}}, effective 2009-05-07.</ref><ref>[http://www.alaskatravel.com/alaska/nome.html Nome Alaska Economy and Transportation]</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn [[World War II]], the civilian Nome Airport shared use of the runway with [[Marks Army Airfield]] for transfer of [[Lend-Lease]] aircraft to the Soviet Union and in 1942, for air defense of the western coast of Alaska. Renamed '''Marks Air Force Base''' in 1948, the military installation was used as a fighter-interceptor forward base until they were pulled back to [[Galena Air Force Station]]. Marks AFB closed in 1950 and an air base squadron was at Nome Airport until December 1956.\n\n==Facilities and aircraft==\nNome Airport resides at [[elevation]] of 38 feet (11 m) above [[mean sea level]]. It has two [[runway]]s with [[asphalt]] surfaces: Runway 10/28 is 6,000 by 150 feet (1,829 x 46 m) and Runway 3/21 is 6,175 by 150 feet (1,882 x 46 m).<ref name=\"FAA\" />\n\nFor the 12-month period ending January 1, 2010, the airport had 28,000 aircraft operations, an average of 76 per day: 54% [[air taxi]], 36% [[general aviation]], 5% [[airline|scheduled commercial]], and 5% [[military aviation|military]]. At that time there were 71 aircraft based at this airport: 72% single-[[aircraft engine|engine]], 17% multi-engine, 7% [[helicopter]], and 4% [[military aircraft|military]].<ref name=\"FAA\" />\n\nFree parking is available at the airport.\n\n==Airlines and destinations==\n===Passenger===\n{{Airport destination list\n| [[Alaska Airlines]] | [[Ted Stevens Anchorage International Airport|Anchorage]], [[Ralph Wien Memorial Airport|Kotzebue]]\n\n| [[Bering Air]] | [[Brevig Mission Airport|Brevig Mission]], [[Council Airport|Council]], [[Elim Airport|Elim]], [[Gambell Airport|Gambell]], [[Golovin Airport|Golovin]], [[Ralph Wien Memorial Airport|Kotzebue]], [[Koyuk Alfred Adams Airport|Koyuk]], [[Port Clarence Coast Guard Station|Port Clarence]], [[Savoonga Airport|Savoonga]], [[Shaktoolik Airport|Shaktoolik]], [[Shishmaref Airport|Shishmaref]], [[St. Michael Airport|St. Michael]], [[Stebbins Airport|Stebbins]], [[Teller Airport|Teller]], [[Tin City LRRS Airport|Tin City]], [[Unalakleet Airport|Unalakleet]], [[Wales Airport (Alaska)|Wales]], [[White Mountain Airport|White Mountain]]<ref>[http://beringair.com/pdf/ome.pdf Bering Air: Nome Flight Schedule] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927063904/http://beringair.com/pdf/ome.pdf |date=2007-09-27 }}. Retrieved 1 June 2009.</ref><br />'''Seasonal:''' [[Diomede Heliport|Diomede]]<br />'''Charter:''' [[Ugolny Airport|Anadyr]], [[Provideniya Bay Airport|Provideniya]]\n| {{nowrap|[[Evergreen Helicopters]]}} | [[Diomede Heliport|Diomede]], [[Wales Airport (Alaska)|Wales]]\n| [[Ravn Alaska]] | [[Brevig Mission Airport|Brevig Mission]], [[Elim Airport|Elim]], [[Gambell Airport|Gambell]], [[Edward G. Pitka Sr. Airport|Galena]], [[Golovin Airport|Golovin]], [[Savoonga Airport|Savoonga]], [[Shaktoolik Airport|Shaktoolik]], [[Shishmaref Airport|Shishmaref]], [[Stebbins Airport|Stebbins]], [[Teller Airport|Teller]], [[Unalakleet Airport|Unalakleet]], [[Wales Airport (Alaska)|Wales]], [[White Mountain Airport|White Mountain]]\n| [[Ryan Air Services|Ryan Air]] | [[Brevig Mission Airport|Brevig Mission]], [[Elim Airport|Elim]], [[Gambell Airport|Gambell]], [[Golovin Airport|Golovin]], [[Savoonga Airport|Savoonga]], [[Shishmaref Airport|Shishmaref]], [[Teller Airport|Teller]], [[Unalakleet Airport|Unalakleet]], [[Wales Airport (Alaska)|Wales]], [[White Mountain Airport|White Mountain]]\n}}\n\n[[File:Nome Airport.jpg|thumb|Nome Airport]]\n\n==In popular culture==\nIn ''[[Call of Duty: Modern Warfare 2]]'', Nome Airport (referred as \"Sand Bravo\" in the game) is featured as one of the targets of Russia during its [[Mainland invasion of the United States|invasion of the United States]] by \"70 bogies\".\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://msrmaps.com/map.aspx?t=2&s=13&lat=64.5122&lon=-165.4452&w=600&h=600&lp=---+None+--- Topographic map] from [[USGS]] ''[[The National Map]]''\n* {{FAA-diagram|01231|Nome Airport (OME)}}\n* {{FAA-procedures|OME|Nome Airport (OME)}}\n{{US-airport2|OME|PAOM}}\n\n[[Category:Airports in the Nome Census Area, Alaska]]\n[[Category:Nome, Alaska]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox airport\n| name         = Nome Airport\n| nativename   = \n| image        = OME-d.jpg\n| image-width  = 250\n| IATA         = OME\n| ICAO         = PAOM\n| FAA          = OME\n| WMO = 70200\n| type         = Public\n| owner        = [[Alaska DOT&PF]] - Northern Region\n| operator     =\n| city-served  = [[Nome, Alaska]]\n| location     = <!--only if different-->\n| elevation-f  = 38\n| coordinates  = {{coord|64|30|44|N|165|26|43|W|region:US-AK_type:airport|display=inline,title}}\n| website      = \n| hub          = [[Bering Air]]\n| pushpin_map            = USA Alaska\n| pushpin_mapsize        = 250\n| pushpin_map_caption    = Location of airport in Alaska\n| pushpin_label          = '''OME'''\n| pushpin_label_position = bottom\n| r1-number    = 10/28\n| r1-length-f  = 6,000\n| r1-surface   = Asphalt\n| r2-number    = 3/21\n| r2-length-f  = 6,175\n| r2-surface   = Asphalt\n| stat-year    = 2010\n| stat1-header = Aircraft operations\n| stat1-data   = 28,000\n| stat2-header = Based aircraft\n| stat2-data   = 71\n| footnotes    = Source: [[Federal Aviation Administration]]<ref name=\"FAA\">{{FAA-airport|ID=OME|use=PU|own=PU|site=50540.*A}}. Federal Aviation Administration. effective May 31, 2012.</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Nome Airport''' {{airport codes|OME|PAOM|OME}} is a state owned, public use [[airport]] located two&nbsp;[[nautical mile]]s (4&nbsp;[[kilometre|km]]) west of the [[central business district]] of [[Nome, Alaska|Nome]], a city in the [[Nome Census Area, Alaska|Nome Census Area]] of the [[U.S. state]] of [[Alaska]].<ref name=\"FAA\" />\n\nAs per [[Federal Aviation Administration]] records, the airport had 61,651 passenger boardings (enplanements) in [[calendar year]] 2017, and 64,122 enplanements in 2018<ref>\n {{cite web\n | url = https://www.faa.gov/airports/planning_capacity/passenger_allcargo_stats/passenger/media/cy18-all-enplanements.pdf\n | title = Calendar Year 2018 Final Revenue Enplanements at All Airports | format = PDF, 1.0 MB\n | publisher = Federal Aviation Administration | date = December 20, 2019\n }}\n</ref> It is included in the [[National Plan of Integrated Airport Systems]] for 2011\u20132015, which [[FAA airport categories|categorized]] it as a ''primary commercial service'' airport (more than 10,000 enplanements per year).<ref>\n {{cite web\n | url = http://www.faa.gov/airports/planning_capacity/npias/reports/media/2011/npias_2011_appA.pdf\n | title = 2011\u20132015 NPIAS Report, Appendix A | format = [[PDF]], 2.03 MB\n | work = [http://www.faa.gov/airports/planning_capacity/npias/reports/index.cfm?sect=2011 National Plan of Integrated Airport Systems]\n | publisher = Federal Aviation Administration | date = October 4, 2010\n }}\n</ref>\n\nThe State of Alaska also operates [[Nome City Field]] {{airport codes|||94Z}}, a public [[general aviation]] airfield located one nautical mile (1.85 [[kilometre|km]]) north of the city.<ref>{{FAA-airport|ID=94Z|use=PU|own=PU|site=50538.*A}}, effective 2009-05-07.</ref><ref>[http://www.alaskatravel.com/alaska/nome.html Nome Alaska Economy and Transportation]</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn [[World War II]], the civilian Nome Airport shared use of the runway with [[Marks Army Airfield]] for transfer of [[Lend-Lease]] aircraft to the Soviet Union and in 1942, for air defense of the western coast of Alaska. Renamed '''Marks Air Force Base''' in 1948, the military installation was used as a fighter-interceptor forward base until they were pulled back to [[Galena Air Force Station]]. Marks AFB closed in 1950 and an air base squadron was at Nome Airport until December 1956.\n\n==Facilities and aircraft==\nNome Airport resides at [[elevation]] of 38 feet (11 m) above [[mean sea level]]. It has two [[runway]]s with [[asphalt]] surfaces: Runway 10/28 is 6,000 by 150 feet (1,829 x 46 m) and Runway 3/21 is 6,175 by 150 feet (1,882 x 46 m).<ref name=\"FAA\" />\n\nFor the 12-month period ending January 1, 2010, the airport had 28,000 aircraft operations, an average of 76 per day: 54% [[air taxi]], 36% [[general aviation]], 5% [[airline|scheduled commercial]], and 5% [[military aviation|military]]. At that time there were 71 aircraft based at this airport: 72% single-[[aircraft engine|engine]], 17% multi-engine, 7% [[helicopter]], and 4% [[military aircraft|military]].<ref name=\"FAA\" />\n\nFree parking is available at the airport.\n\n==Airlines and destinations==\n===Passenger===\n{{Airport destination list\n| [[Alaska Airlines]] | [[Ted Stevens Anchorage International Airport|Anchorage]], [[Ralph Wien Memorial Airport|Kotzebue]]\n\n| [[Bering Air]] | [[Brevig Mission Airport|Brevig Mission]], [[Council Airport|Council]], [[Elim Airport|Elim]], [[Gambell Airport|Gambell]], [[Golovin Airport|Golovin]], [[Ralph Wien Memorial Airport|Kotzebue]], [[Koyuk Alfred Adams Airport|Koyuk]], [[Port Clarence Coast Guard Station|Port Clarence]], [[Savoonga Airport|Savoonga]], [[Shaktoolik Airport|Shaktoolik]], [[Shishmaref Airport|Shishmaref]], [[St. Michael Airport|St. Michael]], [[Stebbins Airport|Stebbins]], [[Teller Airport|Teller]], [[Tin City LRRS Airport|Tin City]], [[Unalakleet Airport|Unalakleet]], [[Wales Airport (Alaska)|Wales]], [[White Mountain Airport|White Mountain]]<ref>[http://beringair.com/pdf/ome.pdf Bering Air: Nome Flight Schedule] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927063904/http://beringair.com/pdf/ome.pdf |date=2007-09-27 }}. Retrieved 1 June 2009.</ref><br />'''Seasonal:''' [[Diomede Heliport|Diomede]]<br />'''Charter:''' [[Ugolny Airport|Anadyr]], [[Provideniya Bay Airport|Provideniya]]\n| {{nowrap|[[Evergreen Helicopters]]}} | [[Diomede Heliport|Diomede]], [[Wales Airport (Alaska)|Wales]]\n| [[Ravn Alaska]] | [[Brevig Mission Airport|Brevig Mission]], [[Elim Airport|Elim]], [[Gambell Airport|Gambell]], [[Edward G. Pitka Sr. Airport|Galena]], [[Golovin Airport|Golovin]], [[Savoonga Airport|Savoonga]], [[Shaktoolik Airport|Shaktoolik]], [[Shishmaref Airport|Shishmaref]], [[Stebbins Airport|Stebbins]], [[Teller Airport|Teller]], [[Unalakleet Airport|Unalakleet]], [[Wales Airport (Alaska)|Wales]], [[White Mountain Airport|White Mountain]]\n| [[Ryan Air Services|Ryan Air]] | [[Brevig Mission Airport|Brevig Mission]], [[Elim Airport|Elim]], [[Gambell Airport|Gambell]], [[Golovin Airport|Golovin]], [[Savoonga Airport|Savoonga]], [[Shishmaref Airport|Shishmaref]], [[Teller Airport|Teller]], [[Unalakleet Airport|Unalakleet]], [[Wales Airport (Alaska)|Wales]], [[White Mountain Airport|White Mountain]]\n}}\n\n[[File:Nome Airport.jpg|thumb|Nome Airport]]\n\n==In popular culture==\nIn ''[[Call of Duty: Modern Warfare 2]]'', Nome Airport (referred as \"Sand Bravo\" in the game) is featured as one of the targets of Russia during its [[Mainland invasion of the United States|invasion of the United States]] by \"70 bogies\".\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://msrmaps.com/map.aspx?t=2&s=13&lat=64.5122&lon=-165.4452&w=600&h=600&lp=---+None+--- Topographic map] from [[USGS]] ''[[The National Map]]''\n* {{FAA-diagram|01231|Nome Airport (OME)}}\n* {{FAA-procedures|OME|Nome Airport (OME)}}\n{{US-airport2|OME|PAOM}}\n\n[[Category:Airports in the Nome Census Area, Alaska]]\n[[Category:Nome, Alaska]]\n", "name_user": "Menchi", "label": "safe", "comment": "hyphenatecompound adjectives", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nome_Airport"}
